05201nam a22006375i 9783110749472DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021946984  a97831107494727 a10.1515/97831107494722doi  a(DE-B1597)582520  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAW0830002bisacsh00aDigital Finance in Europe: Law, Regulation, and Governance /ced. by Heikki Marjosola, Emilios Avgouleas. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4cÂ©2022  a1 online resource (XI, 280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEuropean Company And Financial Law Review - Special Volume ;v50 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aGlobal finance is in the middle of a radical transformation fueled by innovative financial technologies. The coronavirus pandemic has accelerated the digitization of retail financial services in Europe. Institutional interest and digital asset markets are also growing blurring the boundaries between the token economy and traditional finance. Blockchain, AI, quantum computing and decentralised finance (DeFI) are setting the stage for a global battle of business models and philosophies. The post-Brexit EU cannot afford to ignore the promise of digital finance. But the Union is struggling to keep pace with global innovation hubs, particularly when it comes to experimenting with new digital forms of capital raising. Calibrating the EU digital finance strategy is a balancing act that requires a deep understanding of the factors driving the transformation, be they legal, cultural, political or economic, as well as their many implications. The same FinTech inventions that use AI, machine learning and big data to facilitate access to credit may also establish invisible barriers that further social, racial and religious exclusion. The way digital finance actors source, use, and record information presents countless consumer protection concerns. The EU's strategic response has been years in the making and, finally, in September 2020 the Commission released a Digital Finance Package. This special issue collects contributions from leading scholars who scrutinize the challenges digital finance presents for the EU internal market and financial market regulation from multiple public policy perspectives. Author contributions adopt a critical yet constructive and solutions-oriented approach. They aim to provide policy-relevant research and ideas shedding light on the complexities of the digital finance promise. They also offer solid proposals for reform of EU financial services law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 7aLAW / Securities.2bisacsh1 aAvgouleas, Emilios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvgouleas, Emilios, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChiu, Iris H-Y, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorcoran, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrarini, Guido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerner-Beuerle, Carsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiudici, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulms, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangenbucher, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacchiavello, Eugenia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarjosola, Heikki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc